tigates how ordinary people take up financial trading, how they form communities of their own behind their computer screens, and how electronic finance encourages them to trade more and more frequently. Along the way, Preda finds the answer to the paradox of amateur trading-the traders aren't so much seeking monetary rewards in the financial markets, rather the trading itself helps them to fulfill their own personal goals and aspirations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aElectronic trading of securitiesxPsychological aspects. 0aElectronic trading of securities. 0aInvestmentsxDecision making. 0aOnline stockbrokers. 4aelectronic markets. 4aethnography. 4afinance. 4alogic of trading. 4asocial institutions. 4asocial lives. 4atraders. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226427515423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226427515.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles